08022nam a22010095i 9780748635214DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20222009stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486352147 a10.1515/97807486352142doi  a(DE-B1597)616463  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 4aP92.A35bM43 2009eb 7aHIS0010002bisacsh04a302.230962221 aNjogu, Kimani, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMedia and Identity in Africa /cKimani Njogu, John Middleton. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b32 B/W illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aInternational African Seminars : IAS00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tContributors -- tPrologue -- tPart I: The Media, Community and Identity -- t1 Orality, the Media and New Popular Cultures in Africa -- t2 The Media in Social Development in Contemporary Africa -- t3 Language and the Media in Africa: Between the Old Empire and the New -- t4 Reflections on the Media in Africa: Strangers in a Mirror? -- t5 Africa’s Media: Democracy and Belonging -- t6 Representation of Africa in the Western Media: Challenges and Opportunities -- t7 Media Consumerism and Cultural Transformation -- t8 African Intellectuals in a Hostile Media Environment -- tPart II: The Media and Identity: The Global Media -- t9 Publishing in Africa -- t10 Pentecostalism and the Modern Audiovisual Media -- t11 Rekindling Efficacy: Storytelling for Health -- t12 The Media in Education -- t13 Horn of Africa and Kenya Diaspora Websites as Alternative Media Sources -- t14 Popular Dance Music and the Media -- t15 Media Parenting and the Construction of Media Identities in Northern Nigerian Muslim Hausa Video Films -- tPart III: The Media and Identity: The Local Media -- t16 ‘To Make Strange Things Possible’: The Photomontages of the Bakor Photo Studio in Lamu, Kenya -- t17 Musical Images and Imaginations: Tanzania Music Videos -- t18 Political Ridicule: Medialized Notions of ‘Transparent Concealment’ -- t19 Names, Cloth and Identity: A Case from West Africa -- t20 Museums in Africa -- t21 Literary Prizes, Book Prizes and African Writing -- t22 Innovating ‘AlterNative’ Identities: Nairobi Matatu Culture -- t23 Bringing Change through Laughter: Cartooning in Kenya -- t24 Demonic Tradition: Representations of Oathing in Newspaper Coverage of the 1997 Crisis in Coastal Kenya -- tEpilogue: In the Name of Similitude -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aStudies of the media in Africa, incorporating both African and international perspectives, are few. The thirty papers collected here were presented at a seminar organised and hosted by the Kenya-based Twaweza Communications and the International African Institute in Nairobi in 2004. They demonstrate how media outlets are used to perpetuate, question or modify the unequal power relations between the North and the South. Focusing on east Africa, the papers include discussions of the construction of old and new social entities, as defined by class, gender, ethnicity, political and economic differences, wealth, poverty, cultural behaviour, language and religion. The authors illustrate how there is increasing control by local people of traditional and modern forms of media. Globalization is being countered by local responses, within the context of social and cultural identities. Essentially, the book describes the tensions between the global and the local, tensions not often discussed in media studies, thus pioneering new debates.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspectszAfrica. 0aMass mediaxSocial aspectszAfrica. 0aMass mediazAfrica. 4aAfrican Studi